Figure 1
). Next, the capped brood cells were carefully opened with a scalpel, and the foundress and the presumably sexually mature daughters were collected. The daughter (F1) and foundress (P) mites were identified by their pigmentation (

). Once identified, female mites were separated, immediately mounted on nurse bees obtained from LL colony brood frames, and placed in glass flasks (3L) (
Figure 1
). Each glass flask of P or F1 mites harbored thirty nurse bees and ten mites. The flasks were provided with containers with honey and water 
ad libitum
and placed in a chamber with controlled conditions of temperature and humidity (35 ± 1 °C and 60%, respectively) in darkness for 4 days (Figure

1). This period was previously described as the time needed for spermatozoa maturation inside the spermatheca, simulating a phoretic phase (

